CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dendritic spines", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8531649708747864, "span": {"begin": 1735, "end": 1751}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:49807"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pb2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9982842803001404, "span": {"begin": 1792, "end": 1796}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Bdnf exon IV and IX mRNA transcripts", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9551129937171936, "span": {"begin": 1843, "end": 1879}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "exons I and II", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5912463665008545, "span": {"begin": 1923, "end": 1937}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Rat", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9866564273834229, "span": {"begin": 1965, "end": 1968}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:49807"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pb2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990678429603577, "span": {"begin": 1995, "end": 1999}}, {"id": ["mesh:C008261"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lead acetate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9883558750152588, "span": {"begin": 2017, "end": 2029}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:49807"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pb2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9972655773162842, "span": {"begin": 2070, "end": 2074}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BDNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9911370277404785, "span": {"begin": 2150, "end": 2154}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mouse embryonic stem cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.7901325225830078, "span": {"begin": 2184, "end": 2210}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mouse", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9770464301109314, "span": {"begin": 2184, "end": 2189}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ESCs", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9168972373008728, "span": {"begin": 2212, "end": 2216}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:100419743"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Bdnf exon IV", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9577130079269409, "span": {"begin": 2219, "end": 2231}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16044"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "M", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997979998588562, "span": {"begin": 2301, "end": 2302}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:53319"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pb", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2303, "end": 2305}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Bdnf exon IX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9812920093536377, "span": {"begin": 2315, "end": 2327}}], "text": "Include consideration of temporal concordance here   There is no direct evidence linking reduced levels of Ca2+ to decreased BDNF levels as they have not been ever measured both in the same study after exposure to stressors. However, there are findings that strongly link the different elements of Ca2+-dependent signalling events to transcription of BDNF.  Pb2+: Pb2+ decreases the ratio of phosphorylated versus total MeCP2 and consequently MeCP2 maintains its repressor function and prevents BDNF exon IV transcription (Stansfield et al., 2012). MeCP2 gene expression in the frontal cortex is very sensitive to Pb2+ exposure while in the hippocampus, the same gene is affected only at the higher exposure group in rat pups with blood Pb2+ levels 5.8 to 10.3 &mu;g/dl on PND 55 (Schneider et al., 2012). In two different in vivo studies from the same research group, the use of doses of Pb2+ that result in learning and LTP deficits in rats causes decrease in phosphorylation of CREB in cerebral cortex at 14 PND and the same reduction in phosphorylation state of CREB in both cortex and hippocampus at PND 50 (Toscano et al., 2002; 2003). Interestingly, under similar experimental conditions no alteration at the phosphorylation state of CAMKII has been recorded (Toscano et al., 2005). In primary hippocampal neurons exposed to 1 &mu;M Pb2+ for 5 days during the period of synaptogenesis (DIV7&ndash;DIV12), both the cellular and extracellular proBDNF protein levels of mBDNF decrease with the latter to smaller extend (Neal et al., 2010). In the same in vitro model, Pb2+ also decreases dendritic proBDNF protein levels throughout the length of the dendrites and causes impairment of BDNF vesicle transport to sites of release in dendritic spines (Stansfield et al., 2012). Furthermore, Pb2+ treatment resulted in a specific reduction of Bdnf exon IV and IX mRNA transcripts causing no alteration in the expression of exons I and II (Stansfield et al., 2012). Rat pups on PND 25 exposed to Pb2+ (180 and 375-ppm lead acetate in food for 30 days) demonstrated blood Pb2+ levels 5.8 to 10.3 &mu;g/dl on PND 55 and show no change at gene levels of BDNF (Schneider et al., 2012). In mouse embryonic stem cells (ESCs), Bdnf exon IV has been found to be down-regulated in cells treated with 0.1 &micro;M Pb, whereas Bdnf exon IX has been found up-regulated (S&aacute;nchez-Mart&iacute;n et al., 2013).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:24:55 +0000 2026"}